{
  "answer": "**Old English Elegies, Chapter 16** (\"Wraetlic is thes wealstan, wyrde yebraecon; burgstede burston, brosnath enta yeweorc. Hrofas\").\n\nThis chapter describes a ruined city—its strongholds shattered as \"the work of giants,\" with roofs toppled, towers in ruin, and the barred gate plundered.[^1] It then evokes the city's past glories, including its \"bath-houses many,\" before turning to a detailed memory of the baths themselves:[^2]\n\n> Stone courts stood; a stream threw up heat  \n> in a wide surge; a wall enclosed all  \n> within its bright embrace, where the baths were,  \n> hot at their heart. That was a welcome thing.  \n> They let pour then over the grey stone  \n> hot streams [...]  \n> [...] until the round pool grew hot [...][^3]\n\n[^1]: Old English Elegies, [Chapter 16, paragraph p-d0d2bd](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/16-wraetlic-is-thes-wealstan-wyrde-yebraecon-burgsted/translation/#p-d0d2bd).\n[^2]: Old English Elegies, [Chapter 16, paragraph p-ba51da](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/16-wraetlic-is-thes-wealstan-wyrde-yebraecon-burgsted/translation/#p-ba51da).\n[^3]: Old English Elegies, [Chapter 16, paragraph p-dfdbda](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/16-wraetlic-is-thes-wealstan-wyrde-yebraecon-burgsted/translation/#p-dfdbda).",
